{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17720"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10434"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72415"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10434"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57885"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10182"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24487"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24524"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72415"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEarwax is a protective substance found in the external auditory canal of the ear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its composition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glycoproteins and lipids from apocrine glands","Mixed secretions from ceruminous and sebaceous glands with shed epithelial cells","Modified sweat gland secretions and keratin","Secretions from sebaceous glands and shed epithelial cells","Waxy secretions from ceruminous glands and fatty acids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECerumen (earwax) is composed of \u003Cstrong\u003Emixed secretions from ceruminous and sebaceous glands with shed epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E. The ceruminous glands are modified apocrine sweat glands that produce a waxy secretion, while sebaceous glands contribute lipids. These combine with shed epithelial cells to form earwax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretions from sebaceous glands and shed epithelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E lacks the crucial ceruminous gland component which is essential for cerumen formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModified sweat gland secretions and keratin\u003C/strong\u003E only describes the ceruminous gland contribution but fails to acknowledge the important role of sebaceous glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycoproteins and lipids from apocrine glands\u003C/strong\u003E does not account for the contributions from sebaceous glands and shed epithelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaxy secretions from ceruminous glands and fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E omits the important structural component provided by shed epithelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECerumen serves several protective functions including lubrication, antimicrobial activity, and trapping of foreign particles. The natural migration of epithelial cells helps move cerumen and trapped debris outward, providing a self-cleaning mechanism for the ear canal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cerumen (earwax) is produced by ceruminous and sebaceous glands in the external auditory canal.","Cerumen contains antimicrobial proteins, lipids, and shed epithelial cells that protect the ear canal.","The self-cleaning mechanism of the ear canal involves epithelial migration that moves cerumen outward."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57885"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57885"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T16:50:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T16:51:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10434"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72415"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{